This paper is likely to belong to the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category as it deals with improving and personalizing search engines using clickthrough data. It may also belong to the Computational Linguistics (cs.CL) sub-category as it involves analyzing user behavior and search results. The paper also mentions learning methods, which suggests it could belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Additionally, the use of randomized presentation of search results could be related to the Cybersecurity (cs.CY) sub-category. Finally, the paper's focus on collecting unbiased preferences from clickthrough logs could be relevant to the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category.
